<p style="margin-bottom:6pt; padding:0in 5.4pt">56.4%</p>
</td>
</tr><tr><td style="width:233.75pt; border-right-width:1pt; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-left-width:1pt; border-style:none solid solid; border-right-color:windowtext; border-bottom-color:windowtext; border-left-color:windowtext" width="312">
<p style="margin-bottom:6pt; padding:0in 5.4pt">Columbia University</p>
</td>
<td style="width:233.75pt; border-style:none solid solid none; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-bottom-color:windowtext; border-right-width:1pt; border-right-color:windowtext" width="312">
<p style="margin-bottom:6pt; padding:0in 5.4pt">44.6%</p>
</td>
</tr><tr><td style="width:233.75pt; border-right-width:1pt; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-left-width:1pt; border-style:none solid solid; border-right-color:windowtext; border-bottom-color:windowtext; border-left-color:windowtext" width="312">
<p style="margin-bottom:6pt; padding:0in 5.4pt">University of Illinois-Urbana Champaign</p>
</td>
<td style="width:233.75pt; border-style:none solid solid none; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-bottom-color:windowtext; border-right-width:1pt; border-right-color:windowtext" width="312">
<p style="margin-bottom:6pt; padding:0in 5.4pt">25.4%</p>
</td>
</tr></tbody></table><p>University study abroad programs likewise purport to educate American students about foreign countries &mdash; but even given the limited time available, they provide a remarkably superficial education. Dickinson College offers semester-long programs where students spend a majority of their time in a classroom learning about various global theories. Students are abroad for less than a month, but they are encouraged to make broad assumptions based on what they learned in the classroom.<a href="#_ftn330" name="_ftnref330" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">330</sup></span></a> Others provide &ldquo;service-learning study abroad,&rdquo; which simply integrates time abroad into American progressive activism.<a href="#_ftn331" name="_ftnref331" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">331</sup></span></a> Students study abroad to learn that American progressivism is true everywhere.</p>
<p>Universities sometimes take more direct action to promote their globalist agenda. Following President Donald Trump&rsquo;s election in 2016, students and university employees at over 100 college campuses demanded that their schools protect illegal immigrants from American immigration laws by becoming &ldquo;sanctuary campuses.&rdquo;<a href="#_ftn332" name="_ftnref332" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">332</sup></span></a> This aspect of universities&rsquo; globalism imposes ever-more severe restrictions on students&rsquo; everyday speech and actions. Colleges &ldquo;encourage&rdquo; students, with increasingly coercive severity, to call illegal immigrants &ldquo;undocumented immigrants&rdquo; &mdash; even the previous euphemism, &ldquo;illegal immigrants,&rdquo; is now ritually condemned as offensive and &ldquo;dehumanizing.&rdquo;<a href="#_ftn333" name="_ftnref333" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">333</sup></span></a> This aspect of globalism amounts to an institutional endorsement of a mass amnesty of illegal immigrants, and increasingly an endorsement of an &ldquo;open borders&rdquo; immigration policy. Students who resist this administrative imposition of a political policy preference face university-sanctioned ostracism or worse.</p>
<p>Universities&rsquo; globalism entails substantial expenditures not only to recruit wealthy, Americanized foreign students and to provide a social-justice simulacrum of study abroad; it also involves increasing institutional investment in an Orwellian push to brainwash students to support open borders and mass amnesty for illegal immigrants.</p>
<h4>Social Justice</h4>
<p>Social justice activists seek to enforce a &ldquo;fair&rdquo; distribution of wealth, opportunities, and privileges in order to right perceived historical injustice. In America, social justice advocates argue that identity groups such as blacks, women, homosexuals, and illegal immigrants have been historically oppressed and deserve &ldquo;equity&rdquo; for their wrongs, by financial, political, social, and cultural restitution. Social justice advocates desire every person and institution to dedicate their time and attention toward &ldquo;liberating&rdquo; these oppressed groups and repairing historical wrongs. They grant no moral or political legitimacy to any opposition to their goals, and take the suppression of such opposition to be a primary goal of social justice activism.<a href="#_ftn334" name="_ftnref334" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">334</sup></span></a></p>
<p>Social justice activists have taken over much of higher education administration and possess a stranglehold on offices such as Student Affairs, First-Year Experience, Community Engagement, Equity and Inclusion, Title IX, Sustainability, and other miscellaneous offices.<a href="#_ftn335" name="_ftnref335" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">335</sup></span></a> There they dedicate themselves to <i>overcoming privilege</i>, fighting &ldquo;normality&rdquo; (<i>heteronormativity</i>, <i>cisnormativity</i>,&nbsp;<i>Eurocentrism, etc.</i>), &ldquo;anti-racism&rdquo; efforts, and transforming students into career activists.<a href="#_ftn336" name="_ftnref336" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">336</sup></span></a> Universities allocate substantial financial resources to fund social justice activities &mdash; and even to provide salaries for social justice administrators.</p>
