</td>
</tr></tbody></table><p>AOP students receive special treatment and free amenities unavailable to their peers, such as tutors, peer mentors, and additional academic advisors. Aside from the injustice and the inefficacy of such disparate treatment, such efforts divert further substantial sums from what ought to be the core mission of a college &mdash; rigorous education of qualified students.</p>
<table class="MsoTableGrid" style="border:1pt solid windowtext"><tbody><tr><td style="width:467.5pt; border:1pt solid windowtext; border-color: #d1cd7b" width="623">
<p align="center" style="margin-bottom:6pt; text-align:center; padding:0in 5.4pt"><b>Anti-racism: The New Religion on Campus</b></p>
<p style="margin-bottom:6pt; padding:0in 5.4pt">Anti-racism initiatives are the latest trend in campus activism, but it isn&rsquo;t just a transitory academic fashion that will soon be forgotten.</p>
<p style="margin-bottom:6pt; padding:0in 5.4pt">The term came to prominence in the wake of George Floyd&rsquo;s death and the subsequent civil unrest in 2020, though it had previously been used in Ibram X. Kendi&rsquo;s well-known 2019 book <i>How To Be An Antiracist</i>.<a href="#_ftn352" name="_ftnref352" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">352</sup></span></a> Anti-racism is in many ways part of diversity and social justice efforts, but it takes the racial aspect of these ideologies a step further. Proponents of anti-racism suggest that it isn&rsquo;t enough to simply not be racist;<a href="#_ftn353" name="_ftnref353" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">353</sup></span></a> instead, truly &ldquo;good&rdquo; people must be anti-racist. What this translates to is the destruction of institutions that are deemed to perpetuate racial inequities, and active reversal of racial inequalities of outcome through policies like affirmative action.<a href="#_ftn354" name="_ftnref354" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">354</sup></span></a></p>
<p style="margin-bottom:6pt; padding:0in 5.4pt">Anti-racism stands out from other social justice initiatives because of its strong ritualistic and religious elements. To be an anti-racist, you are required to: atone for your &ldquo;sins&rdquo; and those of your ancestors (particularly the &ldquo;sin&rdquo; of being white),<a href="#_ftn355" name="_ftnref355" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">355</sup></span></a> kneel before people of color (POC) and particularly Black Lives Matter activists,<a href="#_ftn356" name="_ftnref356" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">356</sup></span></a>&nbsp;and pay tithes to your black acquaintances as part of reparations for slavery.<a href="#_ftn357" name="_ftnref357" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">357</sup></span></a> Not participating in these rituals results in severe social consequences and the damning label of &ldquo;racist.&rdquo;</p>
<p style="margin-bottom:6pt; padding:0in 5.4pt">It may be too soon to analyze the total effect anti-racism will have on higher education. But even after only a year of its active presence on campus, the push for anti-racism has already resulted in forced &ldquo;anti-racist&rdquo; and bias training among students, faculty, and staff.<a href="#_ftn358" name="_ftnref358" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">358</sup></span></a> Universities do not allow debate upon anti-racism&rsquo;s merits. Administrators are using the enthusiasm for anti-racism to expand diversity positions within their ranks &mdash; even during a historic pandemic and economic downturn that has resulted in the firing of tenured faculty.<a href="#_ftn359" name="_ftnref359" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">359</sup></span></a></p>
</td>
</tr></tbody></table><h4>Sustainability</h4>
<p>Sustainability is an ideology that aims to alter mankind&rsquo;s relationship with the environment, in addition to incorporating radical political goals. It combines environmental activism, social justice, and anti-capitalism to achieve its goals of environmental conservation through extreme measures disguised as science. These include the redistribution of wealth from rich countries to poorer ones, prohibiting or severely restricting the use of industrial resources, mass propaganda and regulation to &ldquo;encourage&rdquo; as great a shift as possible to a pre-industrial lifestyle; and a shift of power toward global authorities, so as to enforce sustainability policy on recalcitrant localities. The United Nations adopted the concept of sustainability as far back as 1987, but the sustainability movement&rsquo;s dynamic core in 2020 lies on college campuses, where sustainability activists use colleges&rsquo; institutional resources to impose sustainability policies and propagandize students.<a href="#_ftn360" name="_ftnref360" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">360</sup></span></a></p>
<p>Sustainability doubles as a rationale for colleges to spend more on administration. Colleges frequently dedicate new offices and departments just to study and promote sustainability &mdash; with all the attendant commitment to salaries and other expenses.</p>
<table class="TableGrid2" style="border:1pt solid windowtext"><tbody><tr><td style="width:467.5pt; border:1pt solid windowtext" width="623">
