<p class="MsoFootnoteText"><span lang="IT" style="background:white"><a href="#_ftnref115" name="_ftn115" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">115</sup></span></a> </span>&ldquo;Average Salary of Full-Time Instructional Faculty on 9-Month Contracts in Degree-Granting Postsecondary Institutions, by Academic Rank, Control and Level of Institution, and Sex: Selected Years, 1970-71 Through 2018-19,&rdquo;&nbsp;<i>Digest of Education Statistics</i>, November 2019,&nbsp;<a href="https://nces.ed.gov/programs/digest/d19/tables/dt19_316.10.asp">https://nces.ed.gov/programs/digest/d19/tables/dt19_316.10.asp</a>; author&rsquo;s calculations.</p>
</div>
<div id="ftn116">
<p class="MsoFootnoteText"><span lang="IT" style="background:white"><a href="#_ftnref116" name="_ftn116" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">116</sup></span></a> </span>LaMont Jones, &ldquo;Growing Proportion of Part-Time Faculty Portends Problems,&rdquo;&nbsp;<i>Diverse</i>, July 11, 2019,&nbsp;<a href="https://diverseeducation.com/article/150958/#:~:text=Tenure%2Dtrack%20faculty%20received%20salary,time%20faculty%2C%20department%20heads%20and">https://diverseeducation.com/article/150958/#:~:text=Tenure%2Dtrack%20faculty%20received%20salary,time%20faculty%2C%20department%20heads%20and</a>; &ldquo;Number of Faculty in Degree-Granting Postsecondary Institutions, by Employment Status, Sex, Control, and Level of Institution: Selected Years, Fall 1970 Through Fall 2018,&rdquo;&nbsp;<i>Digest of Education Statistics</i>, Department of Education, NCES, November 2019,&nbsp;<a href="https://nces.ed.gov/programs/digest/d19/tables/dt19_315.10.asp">https://nces.ed.gov/programs/digest/d19/tables/dt19_315.10.asp</a>.</p>
</div>
<div id="ftn117">
<p class="MsoFootnoteText"><span lang="IT" style="background:white"><a href="#_ftnref117" name="_ftn117" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">117</sup></span></a> </span>Helland and Tabarrok,&nbsp;<i>Why Are the Prices So Damn High?</i>, 20-23.</p>
</div>
<div id="ftn118">
<p class="MsoFootnoteText"><span lang="IT" style="background:white"><a href="#_ftnref118" name="_ftn118" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">118</sup></span></a> </span>Faculty wages are considered in the cost disease because the higher education production function is assumed to be student education. Therefore, the primary labor costs, based by the institution under this production function, are faculty wages. Increases in administration and staff expense are typically considered to be Bowen effects as they relate to bureaucratic incentives.</p>
</div>
