<div id="ftn240">
<p class="MsoFootnoteText"><span lang="IT" style="background:white"><a href="#_ftnref240" name="_ftn240" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">240</sup></span></a> </span>Robert Kelchen, &ldquo;Is Administrative Bloat Really a Big Problem?,&rdquo; blog, May 10, 2018,&nbsp;<a href="https://robertkelchen.com/2018/05/10/is-administrative-bloat-a-problem/">https://robertkelchen.com/2018/05/10/is-administrative-bloat-a-problem/</a>.</p>
</div>
<div id="ftn241">
<p class="MsoFootnoteText"><span lang="IT" style="background:white"><a href="#_ftnref241" name="_ftn241" title=""><span contenteditable="false" tabindex="-1"><sup data-widget="footnotemarker">241</sup></span></a> </span>The fact that as enrollment increases, universities are investing in more costly employees rather than less costly employees, and foregoing possible efficiencies through economies of scale, aligns rather well with Bowen&rsquo;s theory of revenue (discussed elsewhere in this report). Essentially, bloated labor costs appear in universities because they are not cost minimizing.</p>
